member.example:
Intended use of this class is in assignments:

public void SomeMethod(string str) {
m_str = str.CheckNotNull(); // Instead of just `m_str = str;`
}

 Intended use:
 
 var builder = new ImmutableArrayBuilder<int>(count);

 for (...) {
 	builder[i] = ...;
 }

 return builder.GetImmutableArrayAndClear();

 A typical example of usage is providing public read-only view of a private array.
 
 class Example {
 private readonly int[] m_numbers = new int[10];

 public readonly ReadOnlyArray<int> Numbers => m_numbers.AsReadOnlyArray();

 public void DoWork() {
 m_numbers[5] += 42; // This change will be propagated to all owners of ReadOnlyArray.
 }
 }

member.summary:
Sets the capacity of this set to the size of the set (rounded up to nearest prime), unless count is 0, in which case we release references.
This method can be used to minimize a set's memory overhead once it is known that no new elements will be added to the set. To completely clear a set and release all memory referenced by the set, execute the following statements:
set.Clear(); set.TrimExcess();

 To properly implement locking, any code that does instantiation or resolving must follow this pattern:

 
 checkDeadlock();
 lock (m_resolveLock) {
 	enterExternalCall();
 	try {
 		// Your code here.
 	} catch (DependencyResolverException ex) {
 		throw new DependencyResolverException("Helpful message.", ex);
 	} finally {
 		exitExternalCall();
 	}
 }

